summaries.title: Summary 291.1
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniel’s parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Summary 291.2
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Summary 291.3
summaries.summaryText: As a first-generation student, Daniel’s parents provided emotional encouragement but limited academic guidance. Their sacrifices motivated him, though he expressed anxiety about failing to meet expectations. [Part 4/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Faced academic probation warning after struggling with Calculus II due to lack of tutoring access. [Timeline 4]
Faced subtle exclusion in a group design project where her ideas were initially dismissed. [Timeline 3]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 2]
Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 3]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student

quotes.quoteText: If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 4]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 2]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 4]
If I can use my position to make sure everyone gets a fair shot in our projects, that’s what good leadership looks like. [Context 4]
It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 2]
